{
  "doc_id": "17993",
  "text": "Although the signaling pathways that can activate b-cell proliferation have been extensively studied, the factors limiting replication of adult b-cells are less known. Here, we show that miR-7a, a pancreatic b-cell-enriched microRNA, inhibits multiple components of the mTOR signaling pathway (Fig. 7C) . Silencing of miR-7 activated mTOR signaling and promoted pancreatic b-cell proliferation in an mTOR-dependent manner. To our knowledge, this is the first report that uncovers a negative Recent studies implicate other signaling pathways as modulated by miR-7 in other cell types [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Although it is recognized that modulation of mTOR signaling affects pancreatic b-cell growth [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , it was important to directly test the role of mTOR signaling in the ability of miR-7 inhibition to promote b-cell replication. The outcome of rapamycin to abrogate the enhancement of b-cell replication establishes the central role of mTOR signaling in this response.",
